                            <p><b>Introduction</b></p>
                            <p>Fast fashion brands entail mass-market retailers who create products in large quantities in response to the latest trends (Oxford University Press, n.d.). Fast fashion brands waste over 92 million tonnes of waste and consume 79 trillion liters of water per year (Niinimäki et al. 2020). However, the environmental price they impose is often not thought out by us when we buy from such stores; especially, because psychological science shows how we feel a sense of short-lived pleasure known as the “dopamine response” after consuming fast fashion branded products.</p>
                            <p> So, the task for you is to go on a Google search, and find out the latest fast fashion brands; subsequently, ask yourself, “Am I a responsible consumer?” If the answer is no, read this article to find out how to not be a victim of fast fashion brands by understanding the science behind their influence on you!</p>

                            <p><b>Aim of the article</b></p>
                            <p>This article aims to assess socio-economic factors and their underlying psychological bases through concepts such as decision-making, motivation, and thinking, among others. Through this, the article adopts an interdisciplinary approach to understanding how fast fashion brand consumption is driven. Thus, acknowledging how such factors can help us introduce innovative solutions for a more sustainable future.</p>

